<HEADLINE>
<P>
MY BEST RECIPE . . . EXPERIMENT RESULTS IN TASTY CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"I wanted to share one of my best recipes, one which I always receive 
compliments from friends," Cathy Margulies of Los Angeles writes. "I began 
experimenting with a basic chocolate-chip cookie recipe from a friend and 
modified it to my liking." 
</P>
<P>
BEST CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES YOU'LL EVER TASTE 
</P>
<P>
2 cup oats 
</P>
<P>
1 cup margarine 
</P>
<P>
1 cup granulated sugar 
</P>
<P>
1 cup brown sugar 
</P>
<P>
2 eggs 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon vanilla 
</P>
<P>
2 1/2 cups flour 
</P>
<P>
1/4 teaspoon salt 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon baking powder 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon soda 
</P>
<P>
1 (4-ounce) Hershey chocolate bar, frozen, then grated 
</P>
<P>
1 (12-ounce) bag semisweet chocolate chips 
</P>
<P>
1 1/2 cup chopped walnuts 
</P>
<P>
In food processor or blender process oats until of flour consistency. Set 
aside. 
</P>
<P>
Cream together margarine, granulated and brown sugars. Add eggs and vanilla to 
mixture and set aside. 
</P>
<P>
Mix together flour, oat flour, salt, baking powder and soda. Gradually add 
flour mixture to margarine mixture. Mix well. Mix in grated chocolate bar. Add 
chocolate chips and walnuts to mixture. Mixture will be hard to stir. 
</P>
<P>
Drop by tablespoons onto foil-lined, ungreased baking sheet. Flatten each 
cookie slightly. Bake at 375 degrees 7 to 10 minutes, or until desired degree 
of doneness. Makes 5 dozen cookies. 
</P>
<P>
CATHY MARGULIES, Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, BEST CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES YOU'LL EVER TASTE STEVE DYKES / Los Angeles 
